paragraphs.title: Retrieve the animal pictures dataset

rm -f /home/zeppelin/spark-labs/image_classes.csv

paragraphs.title: 3 - Read in pictures to classify in PySpark
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

width = 299
height = 299
import numpy as np
images = []
for image_loc in glob("/home/zeppelin/spark-labs/animal_pictures/*.jpg")[:20]:
    img = Image.open(image_loc)
    img_ar = np.asarray(img.resize((299,299)))
    
    #Only use images with RGB channels
    if len(img_ar.shape) == 3:
        images.append(img_ar)

paragraphs.title: 4 - View a picture
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
print(images[2].shape)
plt.imshow(images[2])
plt.show()

%md 
- Rather than converting DataFrame columns to a vector, we have a numpy array
- We build our own vectors by passing them the numpy array representing the image

paragraphs.title: 5 - Convert to vectors
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

image_row = []
for img in images:
    image_row.append( (Vectors.dense(img.flatten()/255.),))

paragraphs.title: 6 - Create and cache a DataFrame of images
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

data = spark.createDataFrame(image_row,schema=["image"]).cache()

paragraphs.title: 7 - Check how many images we have in our dataset
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

print(data.count())

%md
## Running the Neural Network

- We are going to use a user defined function (UDF) to run the image on the network
- The graph definition has been broadcasted to all nodes, so we can easily recreate the network on all nodes
- The output of this is a vector of 1000 proababilities
    - We return the index of the highest probability category

paragraphs.title: 8 - Create the UDF function to perform the classification
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

def _apply_graph(data):
    with tf.Graph().as_default() as graph:
        graph_def = tf.GraphDef()
        graph_def.ParseFromString(model_graph_broadcasted.value)

        tf.import_graph_def(graph_def, name='inception')
        
        X = graph.get_tensor_by_name('inception/input:0')
        softmax_tensor = graph.get_tensor_by_name('inception/InceptionV3/Predictions/Softmax:0')
        
        with tf.Session() as sess:
            preds = sess.run(softmax_tensor, feed_dict={X: data.toArray().reshape((1,299,299,3))})
            print(preds)
            predictions = np.squeeze(preds)
            print(predictions)
            top_k = predictions.argmax()
            print(predictions.shape)
           # top_k = predictions.argsort()[-1:][::-1]
            
            #print(pred_val[0])
            return str(top_k)
            
apply_graph = udf(_apply_graph)

paragraphs.title: 9 - Perform the classification
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

predictions = data.withColumn('prediction', apply_graph('image')).cache()

paragraphs.title: 10 - View the predictions
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
predictions.show(10)

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

with tf.Graph().as_default() as graph:
        graph_def = tf.GraphDef()
        graph_def.ParseFromString(model_graph_broadcasted.value)

        tf.import_graph_def(graph_def, name='inception')
        
        # show the names of all the operations in the graph we just loaded
        for i, op in enumerate(graph.get_operations()):
           print(i, op.name)
